AGI - It's been exactly six months since October 7, 2023 when an unprecedented raid of Hamas in southern Israel killed 1,170 Israelis and foreigners, most of them civilians. The conflict generated is still unsolved, and develops between peace attempts and a continuous war of words between Tel Aviv is the Islamist movement. Today Israel has withdrawn its ground forces from the south of the Gaza Strip, a partial retreat, accompanied by the statements of the Tel Aviv army that have made known that a "significant force" will continue to operate elsewhere in the Palestinian territory besieged, able to "conduct precise intelligence-based operations".
&nbsp;
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, under intense American pressing to end the massacre of civilians in a Gaza Strip now devastated, intervened saying that Israel is only "a step away from victory" and promised that there will be no truce in the fights until Hamas has released all hostages. As a matter of fact, tomorrow will be a key day for the negotiations in Cairo where the mediators of the United States, Egypt, Qatar, Israel and Hamas will meet, in an attempt to reach a truce and the release of hostages. But Israel does not seem to withdraw from its intent to win over Hamas. "There will be no ceasefire without the return of the hostages. It simply won't happen," said the premier talking to a cabinet meeting. "Israel ready for an agreement - he also added -, but he is not ready to surrender."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Meanwhile air attacks continued to hit Khan Yunis and Rafah at night, according to eyewitnesses. "The 98th commando division ended its mission to Khan Yunis," said the army at AFP. "The division left the Gaza Strip to recover and prepare for future operations," added the armed forces away from the South of the Strip. "We did everything we could there," he let an official know. If Israel's move is or is not a forum for a peace agreement tomorrow when the head of CIA Bill Burns and Qatar's Prime Minister Sheikh Mohammed bin Abdulrahman bin Jassim Al-Thani will join Egyptian officials for indirect talks between Israeli and Hamas delegations.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Behind Tel Aviv's moves there are also the words of US President Joe Biden that last Thursday, irritated by an Israeli attack that killed seven humanitarian operators of a food charity based in the United States, told Netanyahu to want to see a ceasefire and an agreement on the release of hostages and an increase in deliveries of aid. Biden - whose government is Israel's leading supplier of weapons and political supporters - also mentioned subordinating US support to Israel to reduce civilian killing and improve humanitarian conditions. But in the background there is also the threat Iran. The United States expects a "meaning" attack by Tehran next week, targeting Israel or American assets in the region, in response to the Israeli attack in Damascus where major Iranian officers died.
&nbsp;
Washington believes that Iran's attack is "invitable", a vision shared by Israel. And the two governments are working for the attack. Hitting Israel directly would be one of the worst scenarios that the Biden administration is considering, because it could lead to a rapid escalation of tensions in the Middle East. The risk is an enlargement of the conflict with Hamas, something US President Joe Biden has been trying to avoid for months.
&nbsp;
Netanyahu fears him but continues to vent strength and invincibility: "Whoever hurts us or intends to hurt us, we will hurt him. We put this principle into practice, continuously and in the last days," he added today in his speech. "Since October 7 we have been attacked on many fronts by Iran's affiliates, Hamas, Hezbollah, the Houthi, the militias in Iraq and Syria," he said. "Israel - he has concluded - is ready, in defense and in attack, to any attempt to strike us, from any place." Meanwhile, there are almost 1.5 million Palestinians in the area bordering Egypt, many of whom live in tents. Tens of people left Rafah on foot, fearing Israel's background in the area, car and donkey-driven wagons and returned to Khan Yunis today after the Israeli retreat, according to what they show pictures of AFP.
&nbsp;

